    <section>
      <h2><a href="one-ring.html">The One Ring</a></h2>
      <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/One_Ring.png/640px-One_Ring.png" alt="The One Ring" width="100%">
      <p>The One Ring doesn't just make its wearer invisible — it connects them to the Eye of Sauron. While it grants immense power, it’s also a beacon that compromises privacy and autonomy. This duality raises important ethical questions about tools that offer anonymity but also enable surveillance.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2><a href="palantir.html">The Palantír</a></h2>
      <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Palantir.svg/480px-Palantir.svg.png" alt="Palantir" width="100%">
      <p>The Palantíri were meant for communication, but became tools of manipulation and surveillance. Once Sauron gained access, even well-meaning users like Saruman fell under his influence. The Palantír echoes modern concerns about information transparency, manipulation, and the trustworthiness of what we see through our devices.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2><a href="gollum.html">Gollum's Obsession</a></h2>
      <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Gollum_Statue_1.jpg/640px-Gollum_Statue_1.jpg" alt="Gollum" width="100%">
      <p>Though not a magical artifact himself, Gollum is a study in the psychological impact of being surveilled and corrupted. The long-term exposure to the Ring’s power shaped his identity and stripped away his privacy, autonomy, and sense of self.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2><a href="mirror-of-galadriel.html">The Mirror of Galadriel</a></h2>
      <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/Mirror_of_Galadriel.jpg/640px-Mirror_of_Galadriel.jpg" alt="Mirror of Galadriel" width="100%">
      <p>This enchanted mirror reveals possible futures and hidden truths — but only to those who dare to look. While it’s a powerful foresight tool, it raises ethical questions around consent, unintended exposure, and the burden of knowing too much.</p>
    </section>

